00:17:14.750 --> 00:17:15.680
It's really interesting.

00:17:15.680 --> 00:17:19.950
So, the picture is a portrait.

00:17:19.950 --> 00:17:22.140
It's a portrait of John Sachse.

00:17:22.140 --> 00:17:29.410
It was taken by the photographer,
Robert Cornelius in 1841 or 1842.

00:17:29.410 --> 00:17:33.270 position:69%
It's a type of photo called a daguerreotype.

00:17:33.270 --> 00:17:40.170 position:72%
A daguerreotype is a unique photographic image
on a polished sheet of silver-plated copper.

00:17:40.170 --> 00:17:46.570 position:59%
The process was invented in France in
1839 and alter that year Cornelius set

00:17:46.570 --> 00:17:49.960
up the camera he built himself
and made what is now thought

00:17:49.960 --> 00:17:55.630 position:72%
to be the earliest existing American portrait
photograph, which is shown here on the screen.

00:17:55.630 --> 00:18:00.530 position:56%
Cornelius was an amateur chemist who
experimented with photography trying

00:18:00.530 --> 00:18:04.300 position:59%
to make the daguerreotype process fast
enough to be used for portraiture.

00:18:04.300 --> 00:18:08.650 position:66%
These images require a long exposure time,

00:18:08.650 --> 00:18:11.980
during which the subject must
remain as still as possible.

00:18:11.980 --> 00:18:16.230 position:58%
So, several of you noted that he
looked almost pained in that picture.

00:18:16.230 --> 00:18:20.350 position:67%
He had to sit still for a really long time.

00:18:20.350 --> 00:18:23.400
So, as you can see, he certainly
perfected the technique

00:18:23.400 --> 00:18:27.140
by the time he photographed
Sachsen in 1841 or so.

00:18:27.140 --> 00:18:31.530 position:70%
This self-portrait that you see on the screen
is from the Library of Congress collection

00:18:31.530 --> 00:18:33.720 position:67%
and we discuss it in our guide, "Look Back.

00:18:33.720 --> 00:18:34.740
See Further."

00:18:34.740 --> 00:18:39.110
There are so many questions to
consider with these portraits.

00:18:39.110 --> 00:18:44.380 position:64%
You can think about how you would compare
Cornelius's self-portrait or his portrait

00:18:44.380 --> 00:18:50.810 position:58%
of Sachse to the selfies and pictures
of friends that we take today.

00:18:50.810 --> 00:18:53.130
Somebody mentioned earlier
that the picture looked

00:18:53.130 --> 00:18:55.880
like it might have been small,
and, in fact, it was.

00:18:55.880 --> 00:19:04.340 position:69%
It makes you wonder, who is the audience
for a single 2 1/2" by 3 1/4" daguerreotype?

00:19:04.340 --> 00:19:09.930 position:58%
Well, who's the audience for a selfie
that somebody posts on Instagram?

00:19:09.930 --> 00:19:14.380
Cornelius opened Philadelphia's
first daguerreotype studio.

00:19:14.380 --> 00:19:19.270
He took portraits of people who
paid $% for a small daguerreotype.

00:19:19.270 --> 00:19:21.740 position:66%
Just the right size to hold in one's hand.

00:19:21.740 --> 00:19:25.580
The images were slow to make
and expensive to purchase.

00:19:25.580 --> 00:19:31.020
A person may have only ever had one
portrait done in her entire life.

00:19:31.020 --> 00:19:36.990 position:66%
How would you present yourself if you were
only being photographed once in your life?

00:19:36.990 --> 00:19:38.530
Somebody asked, "Was it expensive?"

00:19:38.530 --> 00:19:39.360
It was expensive.

00:19:39.360 --> 00:19:43.640
$5 doesn't seem like much now,
but it certainly was then.

00:19:43.640 --> 00:19:47.330
So, portraitures a really good way
to engage students with looking

00:19:47.330 --> 00:19:50.560
at photography for the first time.

00:19:50.560 --> 00:19:52.290
Portraits are familiar.

00:19:52.290 --> 00:19:56.600 position:64%
Most of us have many portrait photographs
of ourselves or our loved ones,

00:19:56.600 --> 00:20:03.400 position:69%
but historical portrait photographs are also
strange, because the photographic process,

00:20:03.400 --> 00:20:09.460
fashion and social cues were all
quite different 175 years ago.

00:20:09.460 --> 00:20:14.610 position:75%
Using portrait photographs is a great way to get
students started with talking about identity.

00:20:14.610 --> 00:20:18.500 position:66%
Who they are and how to understand others.

